Description: Rhomboidal piece of quartz roughly carved or cut. An inscription as been scored on both large sides opposite to each other; one with an illegible cartouche, the other with two nfr signs. Part of a foundation deposit or game-piece?
Excavator/field collector: Excavated by: Sir William Matthew Flinders Petrie
Curator's comments: "calcite" "natural rhomb (pl. xli. 40) engraved with the name of the spirit Ket in a cartouche, and two nefers or nefrui on the other side", mentioned by W.M.F. Petrie, Tanis ii, Nebesheh and Defenneh, p. 73 § 70.
Bibliographic references: Petrie 1888 / Tanis. Part II. Nebesheh (Am) and Defenneh (Tahpanhes) (p. 73 § 70, p. 111, pl. xl, 40)
Leclère and Spencer 2014 / Tell Dafana Reconsidered: The Archaeology of an Egyptian Frontier Town (p.55, p.176, pl.18)
